                <h2>Who Should NOT Get PRP Treatment</h2>

                <p>While PRP is safe for the vast majority of people, certain medical conditions and circumstances make it inadvisable. Responsible clinics will screen for these contraindications before proceeding:</p>

                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Blood Disorders:</strong> Conditions such as thrombocytopenia (low platelet count), platelet dysfunction syndrome, and haemophilia affect the quality and function of platelets. PRP prepared from blood with compromised platelets will not deliver therapeutic benefit and may pose additional risks.</li>
                    <li><strong>Active Cancer:</strong> Patients with active malignancies should avoid PRP. The concentrated growth factors in PRP promote cell proliferation, which is a concern in the context of active cancer. Patients in remission should consult their oncologist before considering PRP.</li>
                    <li><strong>Pregnancy and Breastfeeding:</strong> PRP is not recommended during pregnancy or breastfeeding as a precautionary measure. While there is no evidence of direct harm, the hormonal changes during pregnancy make it difficult to predict treatment outcomes, and the precautionary principle applies.</li>
                    <li><strong>Anticoagulant Medications:</strong> Patients on blood thinners such as warfarin, heparin, or newer anticoagulants (DOACs) face increased bleeding risk during the injection process. Additionally, these medications can affect platelet function, reducing PRP efficacy. Treatment may be possible after consulting with the prescribing physician about temporarily adjusting medication.</li>
                    <li><strong>Chronic Liver Disease:</strong> Severe liver conditions affect clotting factor production and platelet quality, making PRP less effective and potentially riskier.</li>
                    <li><strong>Active Skin Infections:</strong> Any active bacterial, viral, or fungal infection at the treatment site is a contraindication. PRP should only be administered once the infection has fully resolved.</li>
                    <li><strong>Chronic NSAID Use:</strong> Long-term use of non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (ibuprofen, aspirin, naproxen) can impair platelet function. Patients are typically advised to stop NSAIDs for 7 to 10 days before PRP treatment.</li>
                </ul>

                <p>If you have any of these conditions, it does not necessarily mean PRP is permanently off the table. A qualified specialist can evaluate your individual situation and determine whether PRP is appropriate after your condition is managed or resolved.</p>

                <h2>PRP Safety Compared to Other Treatments</h2>

                <p>To put PRP's safety profile into proper perspective, it helps to compare it against other common treatments for similar conditions:</p>

                <h3>PRP vs Surgical Hair Transplant</h3>
                <p>A <a href="../hair-transplant-in-gurgaon">hair transplant</a> is a surgical procedure involving incisions, donor area harvesting, local anaesthesia, and a recovery period of 7 to 14 days. While modern hair transplant techniques (FUE and FUT) are very safe when performed by skilled surgeons, they carry inherently higher risks than PRP — including surgical infection, scarring, nerve damage, graft failure, and anaesthesia-related complications. PRP involves no incisions, no surgery, no stitches, and zero downtime. For patients with early to moderate hair loss, PRP offers a significantly lower-risk entry point.</p>

                <h3>PRP vs Steroid Injections</h3>
                <p>Corticosteroid injections are commonly used for joint pain, alopecia areata, and inflammatory skin conditions. While effective in the short term, repeated steroid injections carry well-documented risks: skin thinning and atrophy, depigmentation, tendon weakening, fat pad atrophy, and in some cases, adrenal suppression. PRP, by contrast, promotes genuine tissue regeneration without any of these degenerative side effects. Studies have shown that PRP provides comparable or superior long-term outcomes to steroids for many conditions, with a significantly better safety profile.</p>

                <h3>PRP vs Chemical Treatments (Minoxidil and Finasteride)</h3>
                <p>Topical minoxidil can cause scalp irritation, contact dermatitis, and unwanted facial hair growth. Oral finasteride carries risks of sexual side effects including decreased libido, erectile dysfunction, and in rare cases, persistent post-finasteride syndrome. PRP has no systemic side effects — because the growth factors remain localised at the injection site, they do not circulate throughout the body or affect hormonal systems. For patients who cannot tolerate pharmaceutical treatments, PRP represents a safe and effective alternative.</p>

                <h3>PRP vs Synthetic Dermal Fillers</h3>
                <p>Synthetic fillers (hyaluronic acid, calcium hydroxylapatite, poly-L-lactic acid) carry risks of granuloma formation, vascular occlusion, tissue necrosis, and delayed-onset nodules. While these complications are uncommon with skilled injectors, they are inherent risks of introducing foreign substances into tissue. <a href="../face-prp-treatment-in-gurgaon">Facial PRP</a> eliminates these risks entirely because no synthetic material is injected — only your own concentrated growth factors.</p>

