                <h2>How to Choose a Safe PRP Provider</h2>

                <p>Not all PRP clinics are created equal. Your safety depends heavily on where you choose to get treated. Here are the key factors to evaluate — and the red flags to watch for:</p>

                <h3>What to Look For</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Qualified Medical Doctor:</strong> Ensure your PRP is administered by a registered dermatologist, trichologist, or physician — not an aesthetician or unqualified technician.</li>
                    <li><strong>Clean, Professional Clinic:</strong> The treatment environment should be visibly clean, well-organised, and equipped with proper medical infrastructure. Look for clinical-grade examination rooms, not converted beauty parlour setups.</li>
                    <li><strong>Medical-Grade Centrifuge:</strong> Ask about the centrifuge system used. FDA-cleared, medical-grade devices produce superior and more consistent PRP compared to low-cost alternatives.</li>
                    <li><strong>Thorough Consultation:</strong> A responsible provider will conduct a detailed medical evaluation before recommending PRP. They should ask about your health history, medications, allergies, and treatment goals.</li>
                    <li><strong>Verified Patient Reviews:</strong> Check Google reviews, patient testimonials, and before-after galleries. Consistent positive feedback from real patients is a reliable indicator of quality.</li>
                    <li><strong>Transparent Pricing:</strong> The clinic should provide clear pricing upfront with no hidden costs or pressure tactics to buy packages on the spot.</li>
                </ul>

                <h3>Red Flags to Avoid</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Unusually Low Prices:</strong> If a PRP session is priced significantly below the market range, it may indicate the use of substandard equipment, unqualified staff, or compromised sterile practices.</li>
                    <li><strong>No Medical Consultation:</strong> Any clinic that offers to perform PRP without a proper medical evaluation is cutting corners on safety.</li>
                    <li><strong>Pressure Tactics:</strong> Be wary of clinics that push you to commit to treatment immediately or offer aggressive discounts for same-day bookings.</li>
                    <li><strong>Lack of Credentials:</strong> If the clinic cannot provide information about their doctors' qualifications, certifications, or experience, treat it as a serious warning sign.</li>
                    <li><strong>No Aftercare Instructions:</strong> A provider who does not discuss post-treatment care is unlikely to follow proper treatment protocols either.</li>
                </ul>

                <p>Taking the time to research your PRP provider is one of the most important safety measures you can take. When in doubt, <a href="../contact.php">contact our team at DenceSpot Clinic</a> for a free, no-obligation consultation where we can address all your safety concerns.</p>

